Let the three distinct roots of the cubic polynomial be $r_1$, $r_2$, and $r_3$. Then, we have:

(i) $r_1 + r_2 + r_3 = 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)$
(ii) $r_1^2 + r_2^2 + r_3^2 = 3r_1r_2r_3$

We can expand $f(x)$ using the roots:

\begin{align*}
f(x) &= (x-r_1)(x-r_2)(x-r_3) \\
&= x^3 - (r_1 + r_2 + r_3)x^2 \\
&\hspace{15mm}+ (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)x - r_1r_2r_3
\end{align*}

We know that $f(1) = 1$, so we can substitute $x=1$ into the expression above and simplify:

\begin{align*}
1 &= 1 - (r_1 + r_2 + r_3) + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1) - r_1r_2r_3 \\
0 &= -(r_1 + r_2 + r_3) + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1) - r_1r_2r_3 \\
0 &= -(r_1 + r_2 + r_3)(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1 - r_1r_2r_3)
\end{align*}

Since $r_1$, $r_2$, and $r_3$ are distinct, their sum cannot be zero. Therefore, we must have $r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1 - r_1r_2r_3 = 0$.

Now, we can use this fact, along with properties (i) and (ii) above, to solve for $c$:

\begin{align*}
f(x) &= x^3 - (r_1 + r_2 + r_3)x^2 + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)x - r_1r_2r_3 \\
&= x^3 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)x + 3r_1r_2r_3 \\
&= (x^3 - 3x(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1) + 3r_1r_2r_3) + (x^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)x + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2) \\
&= (x-r_1)(x-r_2)(x-r_3) + (x^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)x + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2)
\end{align*}

We know that $r_1$, $r_2$, and $r_3$ are roots of $f(x)$, so we can substitute them into the expression above:

\begin{align*}
0 &= (r_1-r_1)(r_1-r_2)(r_1-r_3) + (r_1^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)r_1 + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2) \\
0 &= (r_2-r_1)(r_2-r_2)(r_2-r_3) + (r_2^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)r_2 + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2) \\
0 &= (r_3-r_1)(r_3-r_2)(r_3-r_3) + (r_3^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)r_3 + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2)
\end{align*}

Simplifying these equations gives us:

\begin{align*}
0 &= r_1^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)r_1 + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2 \\
0 &= r_2^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)r_2 + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2 \\
0 &= r_3^2 - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)r_3 + (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2 \\
\end{align*}

Summing these equations gives us:

\begin{align*}
0 &= (r_1^2 + r_2^2 + r_3^2) - 2(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2 + 3(r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2 \\
0 &= (r_1^2 + r_2^2 + r_3^2) - (r_1r_2 + r_2r_3 + r_3r_1)^2 \\
3r_1r_2r_3 &= r_1^2 + r_2^2 + r_3^2
\end{align*}

But we know that $r_1^2 + r_2^2 + r_3^2 = 3r_1r_2r_3$, so we must have $r_1^2 + r_2^2 + r_3^2 = 3r_1r_2r_3 = 3c$.

Finally, we can use the fact that $f(x) = x^3 + ax^2 + bx + c$ to solve for $c$:

\begin{align*}
c &= \frac{1}{3}(r_1^2 + r_2^2 + r_3^2) \\
&= \frac{1}{3}(3c) \\
&= \boxed{c}
\end{align*}

