\[n^2 + 2n - 1 = (n+1)^2 - 2 \quad \text{and} \quad n^2 + n + \sqrt{2} - 2 = (n+\sqrt{2}-1)(n+1-\sqrt{2}).\]
Substituting these expressions into the product, we get
\begin{align*}
\prod_{n = 1}^{2004} \frac{(n+1)^2-2}{(n+\sqrt{2}-1)(n+1-\sqrt{2})}.
\end{align*}
We can group the terms with $(n+1)$ in the numerator and denominator, and simplify as follows:
\begin{align*}
\prod_{n = 1}^{2004} \frac{(n+1)^2-2}{(n+\sqrt{2}-1)(n+1-\sqrt{2})} &= \prod_{n = 1}^{2004} \frac{(n+1+\sqrt{2}-1)(n+1-\sqrt{2})}{(n+\sqrt{2}-1)(n+1-\sqrt{2})} \\
&=\prod_{n = 1}^{2004} \frac{n+\sqrt{2}+1}{n+\sqrt{2}-1}.
\end{align*}
Now we see that the product telescopes. To see this, write out a few of the terms:
\begin{align*}
\frac{3+\sqrt{2}}{1+\sqrt{2}} \cdot \frac{4+\sqrt{2}}{2+\sqrt{2}} \cdot \frac{5+\sqrt{2}}{3+\sqrt{2}} \cdot \frac{6+\sqrt{2}}{4+\sqrt{2}} \cdots \frac{2005+\sqrt{2}}{2003+\sqrt{2}}.
\end{align*}
Notice that all the terms cancel out except for the first and last ones, which gives us:
\[\frac{2005+\sqrt{2}}{1+\sqrt{2}} = \boxed{(2005 + \sqrt{2})(\sqrt{2} - 1)}.\]
Therefore, the correct answer is $(2005 + \sqrt{2})(\sqrt{2} - 1)$.

