label("$y = ax^2 + bx + c + 1$", (0.2,0.6), E);

dot((0,1 - c), red);
dot((1,(a + b + c) - 1), red);

label("$A$", (0,1 - c), N, red);
label("$B$", (1,(a + b + c) - 1), NE, red);
[/asy]

Then $a + b + c - 1$ and $a + b + c + 1$ have the same sign at $x = 0$ and $x = 1,$ so they have the same sign for $0 \le x \le 1.$  Let $s$ be this common sign.  Then
\begin{align*}
|a| + |b| + |c| &= |a| + \left| b + \frac{a}{2} \cdot 1 \right| + \left| c + a \cdot 1^2 + b \cdot 1 \right| \\
&\ge |a + \frac{a}{2} \cdot s| + |-1 + c + b| \\
&= \frac{3}{2} |a| + |b + c - 1|.
\end{align*}Since $\frac{4}{3} \ge |a| + |b| + |c|,$ $|b + c - 1| \le \frac{1}{3}.$  Then
\[\frac{3}{2} |a| + |b + c - 1| \ge \frac{3}{2} |a| - \frac{1}{3} \ge \frac{3}{2} \left( |a| - \frac{2}{9} \right).\]Hence,
\[\frac{4}{3} \ge |a| + |b| + |c| \ge \frac{3}{2} \left( |a| - \frac{2}{9} \right),\]so $|a| \le \frac{8}{9}.$

We can set $a = \frac{8}{9},$ $b = -\frac{16}{9},$ and $c = \frac{1}{3},$ which forces $|ax^2 + bx + c| \le 1.$  Thus, the largest possible value of $|a| + |b| + |c|$ is $\boxed{\frac{25}{9}}.$

